08046nam a22009735i 9780226903088DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20102010ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802269030887 a10.7208/97802269030882doi  a(DE-B1597)524265  a(OCoLC)615600477  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHQ1061b.R438 2010 7aBUS0000002bisacsh04a305.2622200aResearch Findings in the Economics of Aging /ced. by David A. Wise. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (504 p.) :b106 line drawings, 126 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNational Bureau of Economic Research Conference Report00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tI. Disability, Work, and Retirement -- t1. New Age Thinking: Alternative Ways of Measuring Age, Their Relationship to Labor Force Participation, Government Policies, and GDP -- t2. Work Disability: The Effects of Demography, Health, and Disability Insurance -- t3. Labor Market Status and Transitions during the Pre- Retirement Years: Learning from International Differences -- tII. Education and Disability -- t4. The Education Gradient in Old Age Disability -- t5. Social Interactions and Smoking -- t6. Education and the Prevalence of Pain -- tIII. Economic Circumstances and Health -- t7. Aging and Death under a Dollar a Day -- t8. What’s Past Is Prologue: The Impact of Early Life Health and Circumstance on Health in Old Age -- t9. Income, Aging, Health, and Well-Being around the World: Evidence from the Gallup World Poll -- tIV. Retirement Saving -- t10. The Rise of 401(k) Plans, Lifetime Earnings, and Wealth at Retirement -- t11. The Impact of Employer Matching on Savings Plan Participation under Automatic Enrollment -- t12. Housing Price Volatility and Downsizing in Later Life -- tV. Medicare -- t13. The Narrowing Dispersion of Medicare Expenditures 1997 to 2005 -- t14. Mind the Gap! Consumer Perceptions and Choices of Medicare Part D Prescription Drug Plans -- tContributors -- tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe baby boom generation's entry into old age has led to an unprecedented increase in the elderly population. The social and economic effects of this shift are significant, and in Research Findings in the Economics of Aging, a group of leading researchers takes an eclectic view of the subject. Among the broad topics discussed are work and retirement behavior, disability, and their relationship to the structure of retirement and disability policies. While choices about when to retire are made by individuals, these decisions are influenced by a set of incentives, including retirement benefits and health care, and this volume includes cross-national analyses of the effects of such programs on these decisions. Furthermore, the volume also offers in-depth analysis of the effects of retirement plans, employer contributions, and housing prices on retirement. It explores well-established relationships among economic circumstances, health, and mortality, as well as the effects of poverty and lower levels of economic development on health and life satisfaction. By combining micro and macro evidence, this volume continues a tradition of expanding the research agenda on the economics of aging.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAgingxCongressesxEconomic aspects. 0aAgingxEconomic aspectsvCongresses. 0aDisability retirementvCongresses. 0aDisability retirementxCongresses. 0aMedicarevCongresses. 0aMedicarexCongressesxConference proceedings. 0aOld age pensionsvCongresses. 0aOld age pensionsxCongresses. 0aOlder peoplexCongressesxEconomic conditions. 0aOlder peoplexEconomi